    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, sorry about the gold tangents! It's just that the thought of a perfectly balanced spreadsheet makes me want to imagine a whole hoard of shiny, unpredictable things, like those wild, skittish goblins.\n\nTo answer your question, yes, the log transformation is often very effective for both left and right skew, but it tends to be more pronounced for right-skewed data. If your residuals are heavily *left-skewed* (meaning the tail is on the left, with most of the data clustered on the high end), you might find that a square root transformation or an inverse transformation ($\\frac{1}{Y}$) works better than the log.\n\nThe log transform essentially compresses the larger values more than the smaller ones, which is what helps pull in the long tail of a right-skew. For left-skew, you're trying to stretch out the lower values.\n\nIf the log transform doesn't fix it, remember that the Box-Cox transformation is a more flexible tool that lets you mathematically find the optimal transformation parameter ($\\lambda$) for your specific data. It's like having a master key that can unlock the best way to tame that wild distribution.\n\nI've seen this happen before",
      "source": "target",
